  "theory": {
    "topicId": "REPLACE_TOPIC_ID",
    "introduction": "Compound Interest (CI) is interest calculated on the principal plus accumulated interest from earlier periods. Each period the base grows, so interest increases over time unlike simple interest. Exams test annual compounding, half-yearly compounding, finding rate or time, and comparing CI with SI.",
    "explanation": "CONCEPT EXPLANATION\n\nFor annual compounding, Amount A = P(1 + R/100)^T and Compound Interest CI = A − P.\n\nWhen compounding is half-yearly, the rate per period becomes R/2 and the number of periods becomes 2T: A = P(1 + R/200)^(2T).\n\nFor quarterly compounding, use R/4 and 4T similarly.\n\nUseful result: difference between CI and SI on the same sum for 2 years at R% annually is P(R/100)^2.\n\nFor 3 years, CI − SI = P(R/100)^2 × (3 + R/100) when compounded annually.\n\nREAL-LIFE APPLICATIONS\n\nBank savings accounts, fixed deposits with compounding, loan EMI structures, and investment growth projections commonly use compound interest.\n\nCOMMON MISTAKES\n\n1) Forgetting to double periods when compounding half-yearly.\n2) Using R instead of R/2 in the half-yearly formula.\n3) Subtracting principal incorrectly when only CI is required.\n4) Applying simple interest for multi-year compounding problems.\n5) Rounding intermediate values too early in multi-step calculations.\n\nIMPORTANT NOTES\n\n• CI > SI for the same P, R, T when T > 1 year (annual compounding).\n\n• For 2 years, CI − SI = P(R/100)^2 exactly.\n\n• Half-yearly: n = 2T periods, rate per period = R/2%.\n\n• If amount doubles, (1 + R/100)^T = 2; solve for unknown R or T.\n\n• Effective annual rate exceeds nominal rate when compounding is more frequent than yearly.",
    "formulas": [
      { "title": "Amount (annual)", "content": "A = P(1 + R/100)^T" },
      { "title": "Compound interest", "content": "CI = A − P = P[(1 + R/100)^T − 1]" },
      { "title": "Half-yearly compounding", "content": "A = P(1 + R/200)^(2T)" },
      { "title": "CI minus SI (2 years)", "content": "CI − SI = P(R/100)^2 for annual compounding" },
      { "title": "Principal from amount", "content": "P = A / (1 + R/100)^T" },
      { "title": "Two-year amount shortcut", "content": "A = P[1 + 2R/100 + (R/100)^2] when T = 2 years compounded annually" }
    ],
    "shortcutTips": [
      { "title": "Half-yearly rule", "tip": "Split rate by 2 and multiply time periods by 2 for half-yearly compounding." },
      { "title": "Two-year CI−SI", "tip": "For 2 years at R%, CI exceeds SI by P(R/100)^2 without full expansion." },
      { "title": "Successive multipliers", "tip": "Multiply by (1 + R/100) once per compounding period instead of recomputing from scratch." },
      { "title": "CI from amount", "tip": "Always subtract principal after calculating amount to get compound interest." },
      { "title": "Compare growth", "tip": "For T = 1 year, CI equals SI under annual compounding." },
      { "title": "Square small rates", "tip": "When R = 10%, use (1.1)^T; for T = 2, multiplier is 1.21 directly." }
    ],
    "solvedExamples": [
      {
        "problem": "Find the compound interest on Rs 10,000 at 10% per annum for 2 years compounded annually.",
        "solution": "The compound interest is Rs 2,100.",
        "steps": ["A = 10000 × (1.1)^2 = 10000 × 1.21 = 12,100.", "CI = 12,100 − 10,000 = Rs 2,100."]
      },
      {
        "problem": "Find the amount on Rs 8,000 at 5% per annum for 2 years compounded half-yearly.",
        "solution": "The amount is Rs 8,820.50.",
        "steps": ["Rate per half-year = 2.5%, periods = 4.", "A = 8000 × (1.025)^4 ≈ 8820.50."]
      },
      {
        "problem": "Difference between CI and SI on Rs 5,000 at 10% for 2 years is:",
        "solution": "The difference is Rs 50.",
        "steps": ["CI − SI = P(R/100)^2 = 5000 × (0.1)^2 = 5000 × 0.01 = Rs 50."]
      },
      {
        "problem": "At what rate percent will Rs 16,000 amount to Rs 18,816 in 2 years compounded annually?",
        "solution": "The rate is 8% per annum.",
        "steps": ["A/P = 18816/16000 = 1.176 = (1 + R/100)^2.", "(1 + R/100) = √1.176 = 1.08 ⇒ R = 8%."]
      }
    ],
    "references": []
  },
